reviews.review: Was at the premire Tuesday with a buddy... and i do not understand the critic scores??? yes,. few cheesey scenes and choppy screenplay, but the action is slick, and so is the ending. VERY FUN FILM!!

Honestly, this film was great nothing more to say but the first 30-45 minutes where a bit cheesy and a bit hard to follow but after it got going I was engulfed in what was going on and I couldn't get enough of what I was watching if you're a star wars fan I would 100% recommend you to watch it.

The movie was to fast paced which was kinda bad but kept u on the edge of ur seat and the second phase  and 3rd phase was the best but the 3 phase didn't answer an important question but the ending wasn't really good but if u read kylo ren comic which is really good u would find palatine is anakins dad mby so we have to wait and see
The Rise of Skywalker is a thrilling and emotional closure of the saga by adding a well-done fan-service. It is not the best, nor the worst of Star Wars but it has my approval.

An epic end to a shaky trilogy. Rise of Skywalker was messy, rushed, choppy...but this was inevitable when the film had to make up for two very poor predecessors; there was so little to work with yet so much to answer for, and although it wasnt a smooth ride, it certainly a fun and action-packed one. The movie also relied on nostalgia and fan-service, but is this really a bad thing? 

It is a shame that this trilogy couldn't have had one director and team throughout, as if this trilogy was better-planned, Last Jedi and Rise of Skywalker could have balanced content better. 

Overall however, it was awesome.
First time watching. Also the last I'll ever see. Fucking rubbish.
Uma conclusão épica, para uma saga que se estendeu ao longo de 42 anos

With lack of creative and imagination, a hurried and confusing plot, terrible-developed character (I don't even know why Lucas was criticized by this in 1999 when it seems every character in Episode I is memorable until our days), frustrating explanations of narrative holes (about Palpatine's return and others related), and some absurd kisses, JJ "no risks" Abrams invites to say goodbye to a beloved saga, but concerning my word, it seems more saying goodbye to a dead man that was killed since The Force Awakens. Also I have realized that Abrams can't exploit John Williams's musical talent as a director. Music from VII and IX are less memorable than the rest of the saga's, incluiding VIII.

A disjointed, mess of a film with no heart, emotion or an original idea.  The story was incoherent, the pacing slapdash and the outcome just bewildering.  A bitter disappointment for new and long term Star Wars fans.
